               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1321" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1321" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1321" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1321" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE SMITH</persName>
                  </hi>. I missed a piece of cotton lining, and found it wrapped up in paper at the side of the prisoner's cutting-board; it measured three yards and a quarter—I put it back again, went into another room, made a hole through, and saw the prisoner give the lining to the porter—I had not sold it him—he had no authority to send it away—I asked him where he had sent the porter—he said, "To Crownson's for two caps"—in going to the station he said, "Oh, Mr. Smith! have mercy upon me; you have had others in your employment who have done worse."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Had he not authority to send lining away? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not unless he asked me if he might make up some caps—he might send it to another person's house to be made up, but not to his own.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1322" type="witnessName">
